*Search query: early science explanatory power versus falsifiability limits*

Skip to content Text settings Story text Size Small Standard Large Width * Standard Wide Links Standard Orange * Subscribers only Learn more Minimize to nav A critical issue in the public debates over science is often what the philosophers consider the demarcation question: how do you mark the boundary between the scientific and other fields of inquiry? The standard of falsifiability was a formal method for drawing this boundary, and was heavily advocated by the philosopher Karl Popper. The idea that scientific proposals could always be shown to be wrong remains an important concept in the debate over what defines science. As noted in the introduction to this series, it has also been adopted as part of the formal definition of science used by the US Supreme Court. But there is ongoing debate as to how important falsifiability is in demarcating science from other types of inquiry, and it's unclear whether it actually plays a role in the regular operation of science. As such, I asked those who took the survey (now almost 40 people) the following: Evaluation/falsifiability: Do things typically get falsified, or do they drop out of favor well in advance of conclusive falsifying data? What is the evaluation of competing models based on? Can you describe the general characteristics that people base evaluations on? How big a role do changing interpretations of primary data play in falsification? The following should give you a fairly strong sense of how little the concept has permeated science: despite the clear context provided by the full question, seven responses interpreted falsification in terms of the scientific fraud of manufacturing false data. Beyond that, very few felt that falsification was centrally important in the day-to-day practice of science. Read on for the details . Some aspects of falsification were suggested to be field-specific‚Äîa biologist indicated that physics may falsify based on new data, but biologists took an additive approach, typically incorporating new ideas into old theories. To provide an example of this, I'd note that a strict application of Mendel's laws would not allow for linkage or sex-linked inheritance, yet those patterns are now considered part of the umbrella of "Mendelian inheritance." Meanwhile, other types of inheritance, such as imprinting, are recognized as occurring in parallel with Mendelian inheritance. Despite this, Mendel's ideas are not considered falsified. This additive view extends well beyond biology, however. People in a number of fields suggested that data that might be viewed as falsifying a concept simply reveal the limits to which that concept is generally applicable. A geologist phrased this as, "The theory then is rarely just "wrong", instead you're defining the boundaries under which it gives good predictions... Often it's discovered that some models aren't false as much as they are incomplete. " But moving away from the core sciences, the role of falsifiability became unpredictable. In math, there was no such probing the boundaries of applicability: "In mathematics, falsification means that you found a counterexample to the theorem. This is devastating; you do not come back from that." An engineer suggested a similar approach, noting that, "Ideas get falsified often." Meanwhile, the concept of falsification seemed to be completely absent from computer science, where one person claimed, "if you wait three years the theory that just fallen out of favour will almost certainly turn up again with a fancier name and more money attached." What happens to concepts that turn out to be wrong? Clearly, they don't get incorporated into theories in an additive manner. According to most scientists, the writing tends to be on the wall long before data that can definitively show that they are wrong appears. In some cases, definitive data is never generated; the clear flaws in the concept cause people to stop working on it before the definitive experiments can be designed or performed....

