Skip to content UPDATE: In a comment below this post , reader Peter Beattie calls attention to a short summary of Popper‚Äôs falsifiability criterion that he thinks will be helpful to readers who want the nuances of Popper‚Äôs views. __(...)__ This will be short. As many of us know, Karl Popper demarcated a scientific theory from a nonscientific one because the former is falsifiable ‚Äîthere are experiments or observations that can be done to disprove it. The ‚Äútheory‚Äù of evolution, for example, could be disproven if we regularly found well-dated fossils out of the proper order (like mammals in the Devonian, for instance), if species didn‚Äôt have genetic variation to respond to selection, or if we often found ‚Äúadaptations‚Äù in member of one species that were useful only for another species (e.g., a special nipple on a female mole that was only used for suckling mice). I‚Äôm told that falsification is naive as a criterion for good science, and that scientists no longer accept or use that as a criterion. Some assert that, in contrast, a good scientific theory is one that best explains the data we have. But it seems to me that this is equivalent to falsifiability, for a theory that best explains the data we have could be shown not to explain the data we have. At any rate, putting this musing aside, my question is this: is there any scientific fact or theory that is widely accepted despite the fact that it is not in principle capable of being falsified? I am referring to real theories here, not possible theories. It is my impression, for instance, that string theory in physics isn‚Äôt widely accepted as true simply because we haven‚Äôt found a way to test it‚Äîto test that its predictions are verified or not. And I often hear‚ÄîAnthony Grayling and Hitchens both said this, I believe‚Äîthat a theory that can explain everything explains nothing (i.e., God constructed the process of evolution). In other words, a theory that can‚Äôt be shown wrong is useless. The presupposes falsifiability as a criterion for scientific truth. Englighten me here, but note that this discussion deals with the philosophy of science, so if you think that endeavor is useless you shouldn‚Äôt be responding! Share this: Tweet Click to email a link to a friend (Opens in new window) Email 231 thoughts on ‚Äú Is falsifiability a good criterion for a scientific theory? ‚Äù I think falsifiability is an important defining feature of science, but it is not the only one. In other words, the mere fact your idea is falsifiable does not make it scientific. But I to have heard falsifiability is not the be all and end all of science but most of that centres around the fact other criteria should also be involved, not that falsifiability should be dropped. My thoughts above reconcile the two views, imo. The most convincing alternative to falsifiability as a measure of science is pragmatism, that ideas be judged on their results. However, I don‚Äôt see how that is mutually exclusive with falsifiability. Falsification is more a special case of simplicity‚Ä¶ which criterion Popper also noted as in use. He just got the ultimate philosophical justification wrong. If it is describing testability it isn‚Äôt simplicity, but whether it works at all. However that may be, I think Benton nailed it. Are ther any scientific claims (outside mathematics) that are not falsifiable but are nonetheless provabale? Proven? True? One thinks of astranomical processes distant in time and space ‚Äì but doesn‚Äôt that just underline the fact that they, like all scientific claims are provisional, and while falsifiablity may not be possible or practicable, it remains the gold standard to which all claims aspire? Arguably the most general of hypotheses (see my earlier posts on metaphysics and science) cannot be directly refuted; only refuted by having unfruitful consequences. This is why I would say things like automata theory count as metaphysics (what could refute *that*) and yet automata theory