--> Computer Science > Other Computer Science arXiv:2104.02712v1 (cs) [Submitted on 6 Apr 2021] Title: Hypothesis Formalization: Empirical Findings, Software Limitations, and Design Implications Authors: Eunice Jun , Melissa Birchfield , Nicole de Moura , Jeffrey Heer , Rene Just View a PDF of the paper titled Hypothesis Formalization: Empirical Findings, Software Limitations, and Design Implications, by Eunice Jun and 3 other authors View PDF Abstract: Data analysis requires translating higher level questions and hypotheses into computable statistical models. We present a mixed-methods study aimed at identifying the steps, considerations, and challenges involved in operationalizing hypotheses into statistical models, a process we refer to as hypothesis formalization. In a formative content analysis of research papers, we find that researchers highlight decomposing a hypothesis into sub-hypotheses, selecting proxy variables, and formulating statistical models based on data collection design as key steps. In a lab study, we find that analysts fixated on implementation and shaped their analysis to fit familiar approaches, even if sub-optimal. In an analysis of software tools, we find that tools provide inconsistent, low-level abstractions that may limit the statistical models analysts use to formalize hypotheses. Based on these observations, we characterize hypothesis formalization as a dual-search process balancing conceptual and statistical considerations constrained by data and computation, and discuss implications for future tools. Subjects: Other Computer Science (cs. OH) ; Human-Computer Interaction (cs. HC); Software Engineering (cs. SE) Cite as: arXiv:2104.02712 [cs. OH] (or arXiv:2104.02712v1 [cs. OH] for this version) https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2104.02712 Focus to learn more arXiv-issued DOI via DataCite Submission history From: Eunice Jun [ view email ] [v1] Tue, 6 Apr 2021 21:11:28 UTC (6,427 KB) Full-text links: Access Paper: View a PDF of the paper t